<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[801,1452,1719,1903]" lastBlockId="6.[136,787,279,335]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[839,894,1720,1743]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1073,1719,1743]" class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Lejeuneaceae" genus="Lejeunea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Porellales" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="flava">
<emphasis box="[925,1073,1719,1743]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Lejeunea flava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in tropical and warm-temperate regions of the world and distinguished by ovate-oblong leaves with rounded tips, leaf cells with conspicuous trigones, ± longer than wide underleaves with a cordate base, and gynoecia frequently two in a row on short branches (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="SCHUSTER, R. M." box="[859,1036,1879,1903]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" refId="ref9159" refString="SCHUSTER, R. M. (1980). The Hepaticae and Anthocerotae of North America IV. Columbia University Press, New York." type="book" year="1980">SCHUSTER, 1980</bibRefCitation>
). Stephani’s description of 
<taxonomicName class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Lejeuneaceae" genus="Taxilejeunea" kingdom="Plantae" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="47" order="Porellales" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="tenuiplica">
<emphasis italics="true" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Taxilejeunea tenuiplica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
adds another name to the long list of synonyms of 
<taxonomicName box="[136,217,311,335]" class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Lejeuneaceae" genus="Lejeunea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Porellales" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="flava">
<emphasis box="[136,217,311,335]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">L. flava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
